For each of the {= product_category =} product categories below, name {= category_supplier =}+ Canadian-serving trailer-component suppliers. For every supplier/category pair, provide one public evidence row for each `evidence_facet`: `canadian_operation`, `category_catalog`, and `category_supply_role`.

Product categories:
{= product_category_boundaries =}

Suppliers can be distributors, dealers, manufacturers, specialty component sources, heavy-duty/truck/trailer parts businesses, relevant industrial sources, or official Canadian storefronts. General retail storefronts count only when the cited page is supplier-controlled and supplier-specific for the submitted trailer-component category; an isolated third-party product/SKU page from a broad retailer is not enough. A supplier can recur in multiple categories only when each category earns its own row-specific traceable catalog evidence and explicit category-specific supply-role evidence. The task is provenance, not purchasing guidance: do not rank, recommend, compare prices, collect contact details, request quotes, use account-gated data, or rely on manufacturer/dealer locator pages as a required source class.

Facet bars:
- `canadian_operation`: the page must state or clearly establish that the submitted supplier has a Canadian-serving operation tied to the submitted trailer-component category, not merely to the supplier in general. Count supplier-controlled category pages, product-line pages, catalog pages, or supplier pages where the page-specific title, heading, or main body combines Canadian location/service/manufacturing/shipping language with the submitted category or a clear representative category line. A broad homepage, all-parts page, about page, location page, footer/header address, country selector, `.ca` domain, "Canada" in a retailer brand, product shipping availability, or generic service-area blurb is not enough when it is reusable across unrelated categories or comes from a generic retail SKU page.
- `category_catalog`: the page must be supplier-owned, an official same-organization storefront, or an official supplier-specific line-card/catalog page, and it must visibly show traceable catalog evidence for the submitted supplier and parent category. Count dedicated category pages, line cards, catalog PDFs, or storefront category pages whose main content has two or more category-specific trailer-parts catalog atoms for that row's category: SKUs, part numbers, model numbers, named product titles, named product lines or series, catalog-table rows, or comparably specific source-visible items. Specialist manufacturer/service pages can use multiple named category-specific product or service lines instead of SKUs. Do not count generic retail SKU pages, single-product pages, broad category pages with only one product/card, manufacturer/dealer locators, generic directories, brand-only lists, nav menus, sidebars, broad "all products" pages, broad heavy-duty/fleet pages, broad trailer-accessory pages, reusable mega-storefront pages, or simple category-name/bullet lists when the row is supported only by umbrella labels, reusable navigation, brand headings, or untraceable category terms.
- `category_supply_role`: the page must source-state the submitted supplier's role for the submitted category. Count explicit category-specific statements that the supplier manufactures, custom-builds, stocks, carries, supplies, distributes, is an authorized dealer/distributor for, or provides a named brand/line-card relationship for that category. The supplier role and category must be connected in source text, not inferred from a product page, category page, add-to-cart button, price, availability, brand listing, retailer SKU, or generic storefront status. Generic "we sell trailer parts", "one-stop shop", "products", "brands", store-address, shipping, quote/order language, or a brand page saying a manufacturer offers many categories is not enough unless it also states the submitted supplier's role for the submitted category.

Brand relationships, source-stated price/no-price/quote/account-gated status, and similar catalog metadata may be noted only when the source itself states them and they help describe the evidence. Brand relationships can support `category_supply_role` when they are category-specific, but they are not required for every supplier. None of this metadata should become comparisons or procurement advice.

Requirements:
- The page must identify the named supplier or an obvious same-organization brand/storefront.
- The page must satisfy the submitted `evidence_facet` for the named supplier and parent product category.
